\subsubsection{\Enaex{} ($\dot{E}$ and $\dot{X}$) of light} 
\label{sec:energy_and_exergy_of_light}
%------------------------------

\begin{figure}
\centering
\machinefigure{Lamp}
              {$\dot{W}_1 \; \text{(electricity)}$}
              {$\dot{Q}_2 \; \text{(heat)}, \; T_2$}
              {$\Phi_3 \; \text{(light)}$}
\caption{A lamp that produces heat and light.}
\label{fig:lamp}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:lamp} replaces the heat engine with a lamp 
that produces light instead of work at 3.
Waste heat is still produced at 2, and electricity powers the lamp at 1.
Both electricity and light can be converted to heat without loss, so they are pure energy.
Thus,
%
\begin{equation}
  \dot{E}_1 = \dot{W}_1, \; \dot{E}_2 = \dot{Q}_2, \; \text{and} \; \dot{E}_3 = \Phi_3 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Energy efficiency for Figure~\ref{fig:lamp} is 
%
\begin{equation}  
  \eta_E = \frac{\dot{E}_2 + \dot{E}_3}{\dot{E}_1} = \frac{\dot{Q}_2 + \Phi_3}{\dot{W}_1} = 1 \; ,
\end{equation}
%
and valuable energy efficiency for Figure~\ref{fig:lamp} 
(assuming that light is the valuable output from the lamp) is
%
\begin{equation}
  \eta_{E,v} = \frac{\dot{E}_3}{\dot{E}_1} = \frac{\Phi_3}{\dot{W}_1} < 1 \; .
\end{equation}

Because electricity can be converted to work without loss in a frictionless motor,
electricity is considered pure exergy, i.e., $\phi_{elect} = 1$.
Thus, the exergy of each stream in Figure~\ref{fig:lamp} is given by 
%
\begin{equation}
  \dot{X}_1 = \cancelto{1}{\phi_{elect}} \dot{W}_1 = \dot{W}_1, \; 
              \dot{X}_2 = \left( 1 - \frac{T_0}{T_2} \right) \dot{Q}_2, \; \text{and} \; 
              \dot{X}_3 = \phi_L \Phi_3 \; .
\end{equation}
%
The terms $\Phi_3$ and $\phi_L$ deserve further discussion.

The term $\Phi_3$ is the unweighted luminous power of broad-spectrum electromagnetic~(EM) radiation
emitted by a lamp
in units of energy per unit time.
In general, the EM power of a lamp is a spectral quantity,
meaning that it varies with wavelength.
Spectral luminous power~($\Phi_\lambda$)
is the un-weighted EM emissive power available between any two wavelengths 
such that luminous power~($\Phi$) is given by
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:emissive_power}
  \Phi = \int \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda \; .
\end{equation}
%
Visually, $\Phi$ is the area under a curve of $\Phi_\lambda$ vs.\ $\lambda$.

The term $\phi_L$ is the exergy-to-energy ratio for light.
Recent work by Delgado-Bonal~\cite{Delgado-Bonal:2017aa}
provides a method for calculating $\phi_L$.
(See Section~\ref{sec:phi_light} for details.)
Delgado-Bonal's estimate 
is $\phi_L = 0.931$
for blackbody solar spectrum electromagnetic radiation
\cite[Figure~3]{Delgado-Bonal:2017aa}.
A similar estimate comes from the maximum efficiency 
of converting blackbody electromagnetic radiation (at 5800~K, the temperature of the sun) 
to electricity (pure work and, therefore, pure exergy), 
rejecting waste heat to an ambient temperature of 300~K:
%
\begin{equation}
  \phi_L \approx \eta_C = 1 - \frac{T_0}{T_{sun}} = 1 - \frac{300 \; \text{K}}{5800 \; \text{K}} = 0.948 \; .
\end{equation}
%
