\subsection{Human perception of light} 
\label{sec:human_perception_of_light}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

We noted above that both
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item \enaex{} of light and

  \item \enaex{} efficiency of lamps

\end{enumerate*}
%
are independent of human presence.
But what about human \emph{perception}?

Human beings perceive heat by temperature and light by wavelength.
Human skin can perceive the thermal radiation portion of the broader electromagnetic spectrum,
approximately 100 nm < $\lambda$ < 10,000 nm, and
human skin is differentially sensitive to EM spectrum wavelength.  
Indeed, thermoreceptors in the dermis of skin are important sensors for regulation of body temperature.
****
Need a reference here.---MKH
****
Furthermore,
the potential for heat to do work (pure exergy) is a function of the temperature of heat being transferred.
Because work is the valuable thing when quantifying exergy, 
we account for the importance of temperature when 
quantifying the exergy of heat.

Human eyes perceive only a portion of the electromagnetic spectrum emitted by lamps
(approximately \humaneyesensitivity).
If we define the ``work'' (and, therefore, exergy) of light
to be stimulating visually-sensitive cells in the eye,
it makes sense to account for human perception when 
quantifying the exergy of light.
But how?

Knowing that visual perception of light is a function of wavelength
leads to modifying Equation~\ref{eq:emissive_power}
to include a weighting function~($f_\lambda$) such that
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:weighted_emissive_power}
  \dot{L} = \int f_\lambda \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda \; ,
\end{equation}
%
with $0 \le f_\lambda \le 1$.

Given Equation~\ref{eq:weighted_emissive_power}, 
accounting for human visual perception amounts 
to selecting a functional form for the weighting function $f_\lambda$.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Weighting functions}
\label{sec:weighting_functions}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

For the purposes of this paper, 
at least four options for the weighting function ($f_\lambda$) are apparent.
The first option is degenerate: 
the analyst could decide to ignore the nuances of human visual perception altogether,
implicitly assuming that all EM radiation emitted from a lamp is valuable, 
whether or not it is within the visible portion of the EM spectrum.
For the first option, 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f1}
  f_{\lambda,uw} = 1 \; .
\end{equation}

Second, the analyst could 
deem a lamp's EM radiation to be useful if and only if it \emph{could}
stimulate photoreceptive cells in the human eye,
regardless of the spectral sensitivity of those cells.
In the second option, the analyst excludes the \enoex{} content of light
in wavelengths outside the range of perception by the human eye
when determining the useful \enoex{} of light.
Specifically,
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f2}
f_{\lambda,vis} =
  \begin{cases}
    0 & \lambda < 380 \text{ nm} \\
    1 & 380 \text{ nm} \le \lambda \le 750 \text{ nm} \\
    0 & 750 \text{ nm} < \lambda \\
  \end{cases} \; .
\end{equation}

But the human eye is spectrally sensitive to EM radiation, 
with a sensitivity peak at 555~nm (green)
and lesser sensitivities at both longer and shorter wavelengths.
A third option involves weighting a lamp's emitted EM radiation 
by the photopic sensitivity of the human eye.
The photopic luminosity (pl) function~($V_f$) describes this sensitivity, 
as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:Vis_Graph}.
$V_\lambda$ is the photopic luminosity function, 
first defined by the Commission Internationale de l' Éclairage (CIE)
most recently in 2006(?), and 
it represents the sensitivity of M and L cones
at daytime light levels. **** Need reference here.---MKH ****
So, for Option 3,
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f3}
  f_{\lambda,pl} = V_\lambda \; .
\end{equation}

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:f3} into Equation~\ref{eq:weighted_emissive_power}
provides the basis for calculating a lamp's output of visible light in lumens (lm)
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:lumen}
  \dot{P}_{pl} = 683 \text{ lm/W} \int V_\lambda \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where 683~lm/W is the EM radiation emission of a light source emitting at 555 nm. 
(Note that because lumens are a re-scaling of watts, 
lumens are also a unit of luminous power.)

The photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$) is the industry standard for determining lumen output
of lamps, but it has been criticized for under-representing
the power of wavelengths less than 555~nm, 
a long-wave bias.
The photopic luminosity function
neglects the differential sensitivity of the human eye's other light receptors,
namely the short-wave cones,
rods, and intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (ipRGCs),
which are responsible for vision in low-light settings and
physiological functions such as the regulation of circadian rhythms.

Given that the industry-standard measure of lighting efficiency
is the luminous efficacy
(the quotient between a lamp's lumen output and the power input),
the use of the photopic luminosity function 
under-represents the power at short wavelengths in lighting efficiency estimates.
This state of affairs biases lighting manufacturers to reduce short wavelength
output of lamps, even when short wavelength EM radiation would be beneficial
for biological regulation. 

A fourth option weights a lamps EM radiation output 
by the sensitivity of all five light receptors in the human eye
(not just the M and L cones as in $V_\lambda$). 
The universal luminous efficiency function ($U_\lambda$) **** reference ****
captures the actual, broader sensitivity of the human eye.
So, for option 4,
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f4}
  f_{\lambda,univ} = U_\lambda \; .
\end{equation}

The leftmost column of Figure~\ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps} shows 
the four options for weighting a lamp's EM radiation output
when determining the useful \enoex{} of light.




