The exergy of a non-blackbody lamp
is found by integrating the product of
the specular power distribution~($\Phi_\lambda$),
the specular weighting function~($f_\lambda$), and
the specular exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_\lambda$)
with respect to wavelength.
%
\begin{equation}
  \dot{L}_X = \int \phi_{L\lambda} f_\lambda \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda
\end{equation}

The quotient of $\dot{L}_{X}$ and $\dot{L}$ gives the overall exergy-energy ratio, 
which is specific to each combination of
lamp ($\Phi_\lambda$) and
weighting function ($f_\lambda$).

\begin{equation}
  \phi_{L} = \frac{\dot{L}_{X}}{\dot{L}} 
           = \frac {\int \phi_{L\lambda} f_\lambda \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda}
                       {\int f_\lambda \Phi_\lambda \mathrm{d}\lambda}
\end{equation}


Shan and Zhou (2019) advance this thinking,
developing a methodology which includes
exergy intensity reductions due to
absorption and scattering and spatial scattering,
in addition to Petela's exergy-energy coefficient.
For the purposes of this analysis
we choose not to examine these additional factors.
