%------------------------------
\subsection{Comparison with previous approaches in Societal Exergy Analysis}
\label{sec:compwithSEA}
%------------------------------
%
The luminous (or second law) efficiency of lighting
has previously been calculated in SEA
by taking the quotient of the minimum energy required to produce a given output,
and the energy required to produce a given output by the device in question (Section \ref{sec:divergent_approaches}).

This approach has been recommended for outputs such as light, sound and information
\textit "because the useful output cannot or is not typically measured in energy units"
\cite{Sousa2017}.

For lighting this constitutes taking the quotient
of the theoretical minimum quantity of energy required to emit one lumen,
and the actual energy used to emit one lumen of light by the lamp,
values which are derived by taking the inverse of the luminous efficacy values,
with the equation therefore equivalent to
the quotient of the devices luminous efficacy
and the maximum luminous efficacy.
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{1}{\epsilon_{max}} / \frac{1}{\epsilon_{lamp}} \equiv \frac{1}{\epsilon_{max}} \cdot \frac{\epsilon_{lamp}}{1} \equiv \frac{\epsilon_{lamp}}{\epsilon_{max}}\; ,
\end{equation}
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{\; \; \frac{1}{\epsilon_{max}} \; \; }{\frac{1}{\epsilon_{lamp}}}
       = \frac{1}{\epsilon_{max}} \cdot \frac{\epsilon_{lamp}}{1}
       = \frac{\epsilon_{lamp}}{\epsilon_{max}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\epsilon_{max}$ is equal to the maximum luminous efficacy,
and $\epsilon_{lamp}$ is equal to the luminous efficacy of the lamp.
In the case where $\epsilon_{max}$ is equal to 683 lm/W this equation becomes
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{\epsilon_{lamp}}{683 \text{ lm/W}}\; .
\end{equation}
%
As detailed above in \ref{sec:energy_and_exergy_of_light}
the luminous efficacy of a lamp is equal to the quotient
of the luminous power and electricity consumption of the device, and given by
%
\begin{equation}
 Luminous\ efficacy = \epsilon_{lamp} = \frac {683 \text{ lm/W} \int \dot{P}_\lambda V_\lambda d\lambda}{\dot{W}_1} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
Equation? then becomes,
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac{\frac {683 \text{ lm/W} \int \dot{P}_\lambda V_\lambda d\lambda}{\dot{W}_1}}{683 \text{ lm/W}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
The two instances of 683 lm/W cancel, giving
%
\begin{equation}
  \frac {\int \dot{P}_\lambda V_\lambda d\lambda}{\dot{W}_1}\; .
\end{equation}
%
This is equivalent to the equation for the valuable energy efficiency of light
as given in section \ref{sec:energy_and_exergy_of_light},
%
\begin{equation}
  \eta_{X,v} = \frac{\int \dot{P}_\lambda Wf_\lambda d\lambda}{\dot{W}_1} = \frac{\dot{L}_{useful}}{\dot{W}_1} \; .
\end{equation}

but only if the photopic luminosity function is selected as the weighting function,
and 683 lm/W taken as the maximum luminous efficacy value ($\epsilon_{max}$).

Considering the equivalency of the previous SEA approach
when using a maximum luminous efficacy figure of 683 lm/W,
and the approach detailed in this paper when using the photopic luminosity function,
any future studies which select different weighting functions
are likely to produce considerably different results.
For example, the use of 400 lm/W as the maximum luminous efficacy figure
by Ayres et al (2005) and Guevara et al (2016)
results in lighting efficiencies being overestimated by a factor of $\frac {683}{400}$ = 1.71,
\emph{if} it is decided that light has the greatest utility at a wavelength of 555nm,
and is therefore desired work output.
The choice of any weighting function is a subjective decision for the analyst,
however to provide consistency for SEA community moving forward
we propose to adopt the universal luminosity function in accordance with Rea and Biermann (2018),
\emph{if} the assumption is made that lamps are solely used for illumination in society.
A more comprehensive approach would be to select a representative range of uses for lamps,
which are then assessed based on their respective weighting functions.



